<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-290-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 290 584.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 22 1989 n539 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Capitalizing on fuzzy logic: politics push Chinese researchers toset up shop in Japan.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, R. Colin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fuzzy logic may soon put the power of a supercomputer into adesktop-sized package, and make expert systems and otherartificial intelligence products easier to make and easier to use.andO;Fuzzy logic is simpler and closer to human logic than is thetraditional binary logic of computers, and natural language canreplace artificial programming languages.andP;  In expert systems thenumber of rules needed is reduced eight to ten times in a fuzzysystem.andP;  Pei-zhuang Wang, Director of Beijing University'sInstitute of Fuzzy Systems and Knowledge Engineering, is one ofthousands of Chinese researchers working on fuzzy logic.andP;  Withsome of his students he has founded Apt Instruments Corp, whichmanufactures a stand-alone fuzzy system that can communicate witha host computer.andP;  In 1990 Apt will introduce plug in boards forseveral systems, and eventually a fuzzy PC.andP;  Apt is headquarteredin Tokyo.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apt Instruments Corp. (product development).andO;Topic:     Fuzzy SetsLogic CircuitryResearch and DevelopmentChinaJapanArtificial IntelligenceSupermicrocomputersNatural Language InterfacesBeijing University.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>